The synthesis pathway of CDs and Fe-CDs were shown in Fig. 1a. The possible synthesis mechanisms of Fe-CDs and CDs can be found in Text S1. The size and morphology of Fe-CDs (Figs. 1b-1c) and CDs (Figs. 1d-1e) were determined by TEM. EDS spectra and average particle size were shown in Fig. S1. TEM showed that both Fe-CDs and CDs had a lattice spacing of 0.21 nm, matching the typical distance between graphite layers of (100) facet of sp2 graphitic carbon pattern [36]. The element mapping of Fe-CDs was shown in Figs. 1f-1h, where C, O, and Fe elements were evenly distributed on Fe-CDs. The element mapping of CDs (Fig. S2) also showed the evenly distribution of C and O elements [37]. As depicted in 
                        Fig. 2a, typical diffraction peaks of CDs can be found with unclear diffraction peak of iron in XRD pattern of Fe-CDs, which attributed to the relatively low iron atom doping amount [38]. The functional groups and structure of CDs and Fe-CDs were studied by FT−IR (Fig. 2b). A wide and strong −OH absorption peak appeared at 3402 cm−1 indicated that the surface of Fe-CDs contained more −OH than CDs, which mainly contributed by rich −OH structures of FG and coordination water. The shift of the vibrational absorption peak of the −OH groups to the low wavenumber might be due to the remarkable association of hydroxyl compounds [39]. The absorption peaks at 2965 cm−1, 2932 cm−1 and 1407 cm−1 corresponded to the stretching vibration of the saturated −CH, −CH2 and symmetric deformation vibration of −CH3, respectively [15]. In addition, the absorption peaks at 1628 cm−1 and 1085 cm−1 might be caused by the stretching vibration of CO and C−O [40]. Significantly, the peak at 570 cm−1 corresponding to Fe−O bond also confirmed that Fe atom was successfully doped in Fe-CDs. Typical D−band (sp

